We came here as a party of 5, looking for some very nice Italian eats. This place is located at the Aventura Mall. When you walk in, it feels like you are walking into a real Italian eatery, with these beautiful floors and this wonderful décor. Unfortunately, this is where the enchantment ends. We ordered some mushrooms, a carpaccio, artichoke, Burrata, and the Spiedino to start. The burrata and the Spiedino were excellent, however there was something interesting regarding the Burrata, it is server with a salad on the side however its simply dry and they provide a tomato dressing on the side? The reason why it was a question is because we were not sure how it was supposed to be eaten, as we just mixed it on our plate which led to less then favorable outcomes. The Carpaccio was some very thinly sliced salmon, tuna, and octopus, which was great until you actually tried to get some on your plate and  you realize you are literally ripping up paper thin slices of this fish off the plate. While the dish “looks cool” the actual execution and eating of the dish leaves a lot to be desired as it is so difficult to transfer of the place and eat. Upon scanning the menu this second time to pick out our entrees, we noticed something very interesting about the chef. It seems he loves mushrooms, rather I should say mushroom… Mainly the portobello mushroom. There was a underlying theme here, almost every dish features portobello mushrooms. My wife ordered a lasagna, our guests ordered a Salmon, another Speidino (we liked it that much), and a red seafood soup, I opted out of ordering a full entrée and went with a chicken Caesar salad as none of the entrees caught my eye. I was not in the mood for Chicken breast which was the only poultry they had, and The seafood soup was good, but absolutely nothing special. The Salmon was dry but the lobster cream redeemed the dish overall. The lasagna was heavy and tasted as if it were store bought, and oddly enough the Cesare salad was lacking. I am not sure what exactly it was lacking as I could not put my finger on it. They placed the chicken on the side of the salad and it was very dry. The dressing of the salad was simply missing something, whether it was lacking anchovies, or some other issue I don’t know but it was lacking. Overall I would come here again for the Spiedino, but I don’t think I would go out of my way for what is essentially a high-end grilled cheese sandwich, I really hope we just came on an off day, because judging from other reviews there were dishes I would have liked to order but are simply not on the menu at the time, or perhaps was a special I missed out on.  One person mentioned Ossobucco but we did not see anything, nor were we offered any specials. This was by the way a Friday night.
